# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battle-of-arnemuiden
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The river Scheldt flows through Antwerp, linking it to the North Sea by the river's Westerschelde estuary.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp is about 40 km (25 mi) north of Brussels, and about 15 km (9 mi) south of the Dutch border.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The Port of Antwerp is one of the biggest in the world, ranking second in Europe after Rotterdam and within the top 20 globally.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The city is also known as the hub of the world's diamond trade.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In 2020, the Globalization and World Cities Research Network rated Antwerp as a Gamma + (third level/top tier) Global City.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Both economically and culturally, Antwerp is and has long been an important city in the Low Countries, especially before and during the Spanish Fury (1576) and throughout and after the subsequent Dutch Revolt.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The Stock Exchange in Antwerp, originally built in 1531 and re-built in 1872, was the world's first purpose-built commodity exchange.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In 1920, the city hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The natives of Antwerp are nicknamed *Sinjoren* (Dutch pronunciation: [sɪˈɲoːrə(n)]), after the Spanish honorific *señor* or French *seigneur*, "lord", referring to the Spanish noblemen who ruled the city in the 17th century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The city's population is very diverse, including about 180 nationalities; as of 2019, more than 50% of its population had a parent that was not a Belgian citizen at birth.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A notable community is the Jewish one, as Antwerp is one of the only two cities in Europe (together with London and its Stamford Hill neighbourhood) that is home to a considerable Haredi population in the 21st century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Early recorded versions of the name include *Ando Verpia* on Roman coins found in the city centre, Germanic *Andhunerbo* from around the time Austrasia became a separate kingdom (that is, about 567 CE), and (possibly originally Celtic) *Andoverpis* in Dado's *Life of St.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Eligius* *(Vita Eligii)* from about 700 CE.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] If *Andoverpis* is Celtic in origin, it could mean "those who live on both banks".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] There is a folklore tradition that the name *Antwerpen* is from Dutch *handwerpen* ("hand-throwing").
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A giant called Druon Antigoon is said to have lived near the Scheldt river and extracted a toll from passing boatmen.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] He severed the hand of anyone who did not pay and threw it in the river.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Eventually, the giant was killed by a young hero named Silvius Brabo who cut off the giant's own hand and flung that into the river.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] This is unlikely to be the true origin, but it is celebrated by a statue (illustrated further below) in the city's main market square, the Grote Markt.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Historical Antwerp allegedly had its origins in a Gallo-Roman *vicus*.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Excavations carried out in the oldest section near the Scheldt river in 1952–1961 (ref.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Princeton), produced pottery shards and fragments of glass from the mid-2nd century to the end of the 3rd century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In the 4th century, Antwerp was first named, having been settled by the Germanic Franks.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The Merovingian Antwerp was evangelized by Saint Amand in the 7th century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] *Het Steen* Castle has its origins in the Carolingian period in the 9th century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The castle may have been built after the Viking incursions in the early Middle Ages; in 879 the Normans invaded Flanders.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The surviving structure was built between 1200 and 1225 as a gateway to a larger castle of the Dukes of Brabant which was demolished in the 19th century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] At the end of the 10th century, the Scheldt became the boundary of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp became a margraviate in 980, by the German emperor Otto II, a border province facing the County of Flanders.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In the 11th century, the best-known leader of the First Crusade (1096–1099), Godfrey of Bouillon, was originally Margrave of Antwerp, from 1076 until his death in 1100, though he was later also Duke of Lower Lorraine (1087–1100) and Defender of the Holy Sepulchre (1099–1100).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In the 12th century, Norbert of Xanten established a community of his Premonstratensian canons at St.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp was also the headquarters of Edward III during his early negotiations with Jacob van Artevelde, and his son Lionel, the Duke of Clarence, was born there in 1338.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] After the silting-up of the Zwin and the consequent decline of Bruges, Antwerp, then part of the Duchy of Brabant, grew in importance, with the city doubling its population between 1500 and 1569.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] At the end of the 15th century, the foreign trading houses were transferred from Bruges to Antwerp, and the building assigned to the association of English merchants active in the city is specifically mentioned in 1510.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] During this time, the old Mediterranean trade routes were gradually losing importance and the discovery of new sea routes via Africa to Asia and via the Atlantic to America helped push Antwerp to a position of prominence.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] By 1504, the Portuguese had established Antwerp as one of their main shipping bases, bringing in spices from Asia and trading them for textiles and metal goods.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The city's trade expanded to include cloth from England, Italy and Germany, wines from Germany, France and Spain, salt from France, and wheat from the Baltic.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The city's skilled workers processed soap, fish, sugar, and especially cloth.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Banks helped finance the trade, the merchants, and the manufacturers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp became the sugar capital of Europe, importing the raw commodity from Portuguese and Spanish plantations on both sides of the Atlantic, where it was grown by a mixture of free and forced labour, increasingly with enslaved Africans as the century progressed.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The city attracted Italian and German sugar refiners by 1550, and shipped their refined product to Germany, especially Cologne.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp also had an unusually high number of painters, around 360 in 1560, in a city with a population of roughly 89,000 in 1569 (250 people per painter), it was the most important artistic centre north of the Alps, serving notable painters such as Pieter Bruegel.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Moneylenders and financiers developed a large business lending money all over Europe including the English government in 1544–1574.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] London bankers were too small to operate on that scale, and Antwerp had a highly efficient stock exchange that itself attracted rich bankers from around Europe.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] After the 1570s, the city's banking business declined: England ceased its borrowing in Antwerp in 1574.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Fernand Braudel states that Antwerp became "the centre of the *entire* international economy, something Bruges had never been even at its height." Antwerp had the highest growth rate and was the richest city in Europe at the time.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp's Golden Age is tightly linked to the "Age of Exploration".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] During the first half of the 16th century, Antwerp grew to become the second-largest European city north of the Alps.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Many foreign merchants were resident in the city.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Francesco Guicciardini, the Florentine envoy, stated that hundreds of ships would pass in a day, and 2,000 carts entered the city each week.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Portuguese ships laden with pepper and cinnamon would unload their cargo.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] According to Luc-Normand Tellier "It is estimated that the port of Antwerp was earning the Spanish crown seven times more revenues than the Spanish colonization of the Americas".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Without a long-distance merchant fleet, and governed by an oligarchy of banker-aristocrats forbidden to engage in trade, the economy of Antwerp was foreign-controlled, which made the city very cosmopolitan, with merchants and traders from Venice, Genoa, Ragusa, Spain and Portugal.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp had a policy of toleration, which attracted a large crypto-Jewish community composed of migrants from Spain and Portugal.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] At the beginning of the 16th century, Antwerp accounted for 40% of world trade.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The boom-and-bust cycles and inflationary cost-of-living squeezed less-skilled workers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In the century after 1541, the city's economy and population declined dramatically.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The Portuguese merchants left in 1549, and there was much less trade in English cloth.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Numerous financial bankruptcies began around 1557.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Amsterdam replaced Antwerp as the major trading centre for the region.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The religious revolution of the Reformation erupted in violent riots in August 1566, as in other parts of the Low Countries.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The regent Margaret, Duchess of Parma, was swept aside when Philip II sent the Duke of Alba at the head of an army the following summer.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] When the Dutch revolt against Spain broke out in 1568, commercial trading between Antwerp and the Spanish port of Bilbao collapsed and became impossible.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] On 4 November 1576, Spanish soldiers sacked the city during the so-called Spanish Fury: 8,000 citizens were massacred, several houses burnt down, and over £2 million sterling of damage was done.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Subsequently, the city joined the Union of Utrecht in 1579 and became the capital of the Dutch Revolt.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In 1585, Alessandro Farnese, Duke of Parma and Piacenza, captured it after a long siege and as part of the terms of surrender its Protestant citizens were given two years to settle their affairs before quitting the city.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Most went to the United Provinces in the north, starting the Dutch Golden Age.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp's banking was controlled for a generation by Genoa, and Amsterdam became the new trading centre.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The recognition of the independence of the United Provinces by the Treaty of Münster in 1648 stipulated that the Scheldt should be closed to navigation, which destroyed Antwerp's trading activities.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] This impediment remained in force until 1863, although the provisions were relaxed during French rule from 1795 to 1814, and also during the time Belgium formed part of the Kingdom of the United Netherlands (1815 to 1830).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Napoleon hoped that by making Antwerp's harbour the finest in Europe he would be able to counter the Port of London and hamper British growth.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] However, he was defeated at the Battle of Waterloo before he could see the plan through.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In 1830, the city was captured by the Belgian insurgents, but the citadel continued to be held by a Dutch garrison under General David Hendrik Chassé.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] For a time, Chassé subjected the town to periodic bombardment which inflicted much damage, and at the end of 1832, the citadel itself was besieged by the French Northern Army commanded by Marechal Gerard.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] During this attack, the town was further damaged.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In December 1832, after a gallant defence, Chassé made an honourable surrender, ending the Siege of Antwerp (1832).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Later that century, a double ring of Brialmont Fortresses was constructed some 10 km (6 mi) from the city centre, as Antwerp was considered vital for the survival of the young Belgian state.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] And in 1894 Antwerp presented itself to the world via a World's Fair attended by 3 million.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp was the first city to host the World Gymnastics Championships, in 1903.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] During World War I, the city became the fallback point of the Belgian Army after the defeat at Liège.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The Siege of Antwerp lasted for 11 days, but the city was taken after heavy fighting by the German Army, and the Belgians were forced to retreat westwards.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp remained under German occupation until the Armistice.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A few years later, Antwerp hosted the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] During World War II, the city was an important strategic target because of its port.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It was occupied by Germany on 18 May 1940 and liberated by the British 11th Armoured Division on 4 September 1944.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] After this, the Germans attempted to destroy the Port of Antwerp, which was used by the Allies to bring new material ashore.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Thousands of Rheinbote, V-1 and V-2 missiles were fired (more V-2s than used on all other targets during the entire war combined), causing severe damage to the city but failed to destroy the port due to poor accuracy.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] After the war, Antwerp, which had already had a sizeable Jewish population before the war, once again became a major European centre of Haredi (and particularly Hasidic) Orthodox Judaism.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A Ten-Year Plan for the port of Antwerp (1956–1965) expanded and modernized the port's infrastructure with national funding to build a set of canal docks.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The broader aim was to facilitate the growth of the north-eastern Antwerp metropolitan region, which attracted new industry based on a flexible and strategic implementation of the project as a co-production between various authorities and private parties.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The plan succeeded in extending the linear layout along the Scheldt river by connecting new satellite communities to the main strip.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Starting in the 1990s, Antwerp rebranded itself as a world-class fashion centre.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Emphasizing the avant-garde, it tried to compete with London, Milan, New York and Paris.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It emerged from organized tourism and mega-cultural events.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The municipality comprises the city of Antwerp proper and several towns.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In 1958, in preparation of the 10-year development plan for the Port of Antwerp, the municipalities of Berendrecht-Zandvliet-Lillo were integrated into the city territory and lost their administrative independence.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] During the 1983 merger of municipalities, conducted by the Belgian government as an administrative simplification, the municipalities of Berchem, Borgerhout, Deurne, Ekeren, Hoboken, Merksem and Wilrijk were merged into the city.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] At that time the city was also divided into the districts mentioned above.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Simultaneously, districts received an appointed district council; later district councils became elected bodies.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The neighbouring municipality of Borsbeek declared the intention to become the tenth district of the city of Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Since January 2025, Borsbeek has been a district of the city of Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] With the exception of Ekeren and Berendrecht-Zandvliet-Lillo, all the districts form together one contiguous inhabited area.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The former town halls have been converted into district halls and the former town centres are now local main streets within the larger urban agglomeration.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp consists of the following neighbourhoods.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Encompassing the area between the river and the Spanish fortification walls, this is the historical heart of Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] On the place of the Spanish walls is now an avenue called *de Leien* in Dutch or *den Boulevard* in the local dialect.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Tourist sights such as the Cathedral are located here, but also more mundane places.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerpen-Noord or synonymously 2060 is a densely populated part of the city, and the most diverse one as well.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] This is not a neighbourhood by itself, but is the postal code for the remaining quarters of the district that lie between *de Leien* and the ringway.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] United with the city in 1923, Linkeroever ("Left bank") consists of the former polders of Zwijndrecht and Burcht.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp-Berchem: Vibrant district, rich history, lively streets, major transportation hub.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp's architecture is a blend of old and new, with a cultural heritage spanning from the Gothic and Renaissance periods to contemporary designs.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In the 16th century, the city was noted for the wealth of its citizens (*Antwerpia nummis*).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The houses of these wealthy merchants and manufacturers have been preserved throughout the city.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] However, fire has destroyed several old buildings, such as the house of the Hanseatic League on the northern quays, in 1891.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] During World War II, the city also suffered considerable damage from V-bombs.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp is also home to a wealth of historic Gothic, Baroque and Renaissance-style buildings, such as the Antwerp City Hall, the Cathedral of Our Lady, the St.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Charles Borromeo Church and the Vleeshuis Museum.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp offers a diverse range of parks and recreational areas for locals and tourists to explore.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] One of the most popular attractions is the Antwerp Zoo.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It opened on 21 July 1843, making it one of the oldest and most famous zoos in the world.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The zoo covers an area of 10 hectares and is home to more than 5,000 animals from over 950 species.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The zoo is located right next to Antwerp Central Station on the Koningin Astridplein.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp Zoo has played its role in preservation and breeding programmes for several endangered species, including the okapi, the Przewalski horse, the Congo peafowl, the bonobo, the golden-headed lion tamarin, the European otter, and the Knysna seahorse.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] They take part in the European Endangered Species Programme.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] On 1 January 1983 the entire park (architecture and garden) was listed as a monument.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*), with cool winters, warm summers and frequent, though light, precipitation throughout the year.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Due to the influence of the Gulf Stream, Antwerp has a relatively mild climate throughout the year, with the average temperature fluctuating between 4 °C (39 °F) and 19 °C (66 °F) throughout the year.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Although Antwerp was formerly a fortified city, hardly anything remains of the former enceinte, only some remains of the city wall can be seen near the Vleeshuis museum at the corner of Bloedberg and Burchtgracht.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] *Steen* castle on the Scheldt-quai is the gate wing of the demolished castle of the Dukes of Brabant.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It was partly reconstructed in the 19th century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp's development as a fortified city is documented between the 10th and the 20th century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] This is the population of the city of Antwerp only, not of the larger current municipality of the same name.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In 2010, 36% to 39% of the inhabitants of Antwerp had foreign origins.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A study projected that in 2020, 55% of the population would be of immigrant background, either first, second, or third generation.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] After the Holocaust and the murder of its many Jews, Antwerp became a major centre for Orthodox Jews.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] At present, about 15,000 Haredi Jews, many of them Hasidic, live in Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The city has three official Jewish congregations: Shomrei Hadass, headed by Rabbi Pinchas Padwa; Machsike Hadass, headed by Rabbi Aron Schiff (formerly by Chief Rabbi Chaim Kreiswirth); and the Portuguese Community Ben Moshe.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp has an extensive network of synagogues, shops, schools and organizations.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Significant Hasidic movements in Antwerp include Pshevorsk, based in Antwerp, as well as branches of Satmar, Belz, Bobov, Ger, Skver, Klausenburg, Vizhnitz and several others.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Rabbi Chaim Kreiswirth, chief rabbi of the Machsike Hadas community, who died in 2001, was arguably one of the better known personalities to have been based in Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] An attempt to have a street named after him has received the support of the Town Hall and is in the process of being implemented.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The Jains in Belgium are estimated to be around about 1,500 people.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The majority live in Antwerp, mostly involved in the very lucrative diamond business.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Belgian Indian Jains control two-thirds of the rough diamonds trade and supplied India with roughly 36% of their rough diamonds.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A major temple, with a cultural centre, has been built in Antwerp (Wilrijk).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Ramesh Mehta, a Jain, is a member of the Belgian Council of Religious Leaders, put up on 17 December 2009.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Significant Armenian communities reside in Antwerp, many of whom are descendants of traders who settled during the 19th century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Most Armenian Belgians are adherents of the Armenian Apostolic Church, while a smaller number are adherents of the Armenian Catholic Church and Armenian Evangelical Church.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] One of the important sectors that Armenian communities in Antwerp excel at and are involved in is the diamond trade business, that based primarily in the diamond district.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Some of the famous Armenian families involved in the diamond business in the city are the Artinians, Arslanians, Aslanians, Barsamians and the Osganians.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] According to the American Association of Port Authorities, the port of Antwerp was the seventeenth largest port in the world in 2005 (by tonnage), and second only to Rotterdam in Europe.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It handled 235.2 million tons of cargo in 2018.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Importantly it handles high volumes of economically attractive general and project cargo, as well as bulk cargo.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp's docklands, with five oil refineries, are home to a massive concentration of petrochemical industries, second only to the petrochemical cluster in Houston, Texas.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Electricity generation is also an important activity, with four nuclear power plants at Doel, a conventional power station in Kallo, as well as several smaller combined cycle plants.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] There is a wind farm in the northern part of the port area.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] There are plans to extend this in the period 2014–2020.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The old Belgian bluestone quays bordering the Scheldt for a distance of 5.6 km (3.5 mi) to the north and south of the city centre have been retained for their sentimental value and are used mainly by cruise ships and short sea shipping.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp's other great mainstay is the diamond trade that takes place largely within the diamond district.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] 85 percent of the world's rough diamonds pass through the district annually, and in 2011 turnover in the industry was $56 billion.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The city has four diamond bourses: the Diamond Club of Antwerp, the Beurs voor Diamanthandel, the Antwerpsche Diamantkring and the Vrije Diamanthandel.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp's history in the diamond trade dates back to as early as the sixteenth century, with the first diamond cutters guild being introduced in 1584.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The industry never disappeared from Antwerp, and even experienced a second boom in the early twentieth century.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] By the year 1924, Antwerp had over 13,000 diamond finishers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Since World War II families of the large Hasidic Jewish community have dominated Antwerp's diamond trading industry, although the last two decades have seen Indian and Maronite Christians from Lebanon and Armenian, traders become increasingly important.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The district was the site of the 2003 Antwerp diamond heist, the largest diamond theft of all time.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp World Diamond Centre, (AWDC) the successor to the *Hoge Raad voor Diamant*, plays an important role in setting standards, regulating professional ethics, training and promoting the interests of Antwerp as the capital of the diamond industry.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In recent years Antwerp has seen a downturn in the diamond business, with the industry shifting to cheaper labor markets such as Dubai or India.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The industry has avoided the 2022 European sanctions against Russia although the imports from Alrosa have diminished.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] If banned, the AWDC claims 10,000 jobs would be at risk.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp is the focus of lines to the north to Essen and the Netherlands, east to Turnhout, south to Mechelen, Brussels and Charleroi, and southwest to Ghent and Ostend.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It is served by international and Thalys trains to Amsterdam, Rotterdam and Paris, and national trains to Ghent, Bruges, Ostend, Brussels, Charleroi, Hasselt, Liège, Leuven and Turnhout.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp Central station is an architectural monument in itself, and is mentioned in W G Sebald's novel *Austerlitz*.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Prior to the completion in 2007 of a tunnel that runs northwards under the city centre to emerge at the old Antwerp Dam station, Central was a terminus.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Trains from Brussels to the Netherlands had to either reverse at Central or call only at Berchem station, 2 km (1 mi) to the south, and then describe a semicircle to the east, round the Singel.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Now, they call at the new lower level of the station before continuing in the same direction.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Antwerp is also home to Antwerpen-Noord, the largest classification yard for freight in Belgium and the second largest in Europe.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The majority of freight trains in Belgium depart from or arrive here.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It has two classification humps and over a hundred tracks.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The city has a web of tram and bus lines operated by De Lijn and providing access to the city centre, suburbs and the Left Bank.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The tram network has 14 lines, of which the underground section is called the "premetro" and includes a tunnel under the river.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The Franklin Rooseveltplaats functions as the city's main hub for local and regional bus lines.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] However, there has been an evolution to end regional lines at transportation hubs more outward of the city centre, such as Zuid and Luchtbal.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A six-lane motorway bypass encircles much of the city centre and runs through the urban residential area of Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Known locally as the "Ring" it offers motorway connections to Brussels, Hasselt and Liège, Ghent, Lille and Bruges and Breda and Bergen op Zoom (Netherlands).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The banks of the Scheldt are linked by three road tunnels (in order of construction): the Waasland Tunnel (1934), the Kennedy Tunnel (1967) and the Liefkenshoek Tunnel (1991).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Daily congestion on the Ring led to a fourth high-volume highway link called the "Oosterweelconnection" being proposed.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It would have entailed the construction of a long viaduct and bridge (the *Lange Wapper*) over the docks on the north side of the city in combination with the widening of the existing motorway into a 14-lane motorway; these plans were eventually rejected in a 2009 public referendum.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In September 2010 the Flemish Government decided to replace the bridge by a series of tunnels.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] There are ideas to cover the Ring in a similar way as happened around Paris, Hamburg, Madrid and other cities.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] This would reconnect the city with its suburbs and would provide development opportunities to accommodate part of the foreseen population growth in Antwerp which currently are not possible because of the pollution and noise generated by the traffic on the Ring.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] An old plan to build an R2 outer ring road outside the built-up urban area around the Antwerp agglomeration for port-related traffic and transit traffic never materialized.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In 2017 it was finally decided to complete the ringway of Antwerp with a new tunnel crossing the Scheldt.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In a compromise with civil society, it has equally been decided that the ringway will in the long term completely be covered.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] This compromise is called the *Toekomstverbond* ("Agreement for the future").
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Part of the same agreement is that highways further away from the city centre will be further developed and that the number of motorized trips in all transportation should be reduced to 50%.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Many FlixBuses have a stop at the central Franklin Rooseveltplaats.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A small airport, Antwerp International Airport, is located in the district of Deurne.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The airport is mainly used for business travel.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Flying Group, the largest business jet service in Benelux and France, has its headquarters there and several maintenance sheds and hangars for their private jets.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] There are also some regularly scheduled flights by TUI fly with direct connectivity to Spain, Croatia, Italy, Austria and Morocco.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Sky Alps operates a 2-3x weekly connection to Bolzano Airport.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] A bus service connects the airport to the city centre.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The runway has increased in length, and there is now direct connectivity to Spain, Germany, France, Italy, and Greece from the city of Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Belgium's major international airport, Brussels Airport, is about 45 km (28 mi) from the city of Antwerp, and connects the city worldwide.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It is connected to the city centre by bus, and also by train.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The new *Diabolo* rail connection provides a direct fast train connection between Antwerp and Brussels Airport as of the summer of 2012.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] There is also a direct rail service between Antwerp (calling at Central and Berchem stations) and Charleroi South station, with a connecting buslink to Brussels South Charleroi Airport, which runs twice per hour on working days.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Since 2017 there has been a regular water ferry halting at the city centre, connecting it with towns up and down the river Scheldt from Kruibeke to Lillo.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] It is popular with both commuting port laborers and cyclist making a day trip.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] The current city council was elected in the 2024 local elections, with its governing coalition consisting of the parties New Flemish Alliance and Vooruit, led by acting mayor Els van Doesburg (N-VA).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In the 16th and 17th century important mayors include Philips of Marnix, Lord of Saint-Aldegonde, Anthony van Stralen, Lord of Merksem and Nicolaas II Rockox.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] In the early years after Belgian independence, Antwerp was governed by Catholic-Unionist mayors.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Between 1848 and 1921, all mayors were from the Liberal Party (except for the so-called Meeting-intermezzo between 1863 and 1872).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Between 1921 and 1932, the city had a Catholic mayor again: Frans Van Cauwelaert.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] From 1932 onwards and up until 2013, all mayors belonged to the Social Democrat party: Camille Huysmans, Lode Craeybeckx, Frans Detiège and Mathilde Schroyens, and after the municipality fusion: Bob Cools, Leona Detiège and Patrick Janssens.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p01] Since February 2025, the acting mayor is the Flemish nationalist Els van Doesburg, belonging to the Flemish separatist party New Flemish Alliance.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp had an artistic reputation in the 17th century, based on its school of painting, which included Rubens, Van Dyck, Jordaens, the Teniers and many others.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp is the home of the Antwerp Jazz Club (AJC), founded in 1938 and located on the square Grote Markt since 1994.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp also has various concert halls, such as the Stadsschouwburg, the Bourlaschouwburg, the Flemish Opera, the Arenbergschouwburg and the Koningin Elisabethzaal; the latter being the home of the Antwerp Symphony Orchestra.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Large (pop) performances are often held in the Sportpaleis or in the Lotto Arena.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] These event halls are located in Merksem.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] In addition, there are other well-known venues like De Roma and Trix, both of which are located in Borgerhout.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] A band originating in Antwerp achieving major international success is Deus.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Some well known festivals around the city are: Linkerwoofer, a pop-rock music festival located at the left bank of the Scheldt.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] This music festival starts in August and mostly local Belgian musicians play and perform in this event.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Jazz Middelheim is an annual summer jazz festival in the Middelheim Park.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Tomorrowland is probably the most famous festival to arise from Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Though the festival is effectively located 15 km (10 mi) south of the city in Boom, its founders in the past organised a festival ('Antwerp is burning') within city limits.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The office of the company behind Tomorrowland (weareone.world bvba) is located in the heart of the city.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The company founders are involved in conceptualising urban planning concepts for specific Antwerp areas and are known to invite their favourite Antwerp food places to set up a pop-up at the festival.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Sfinks festival is a global pop festival that takes place annually in Boechout, a village southeast of Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Other popular festivals are Fire Is Gold, Ampere Open Air and Vaag Outdoor focusing more on hip-hop music, house and techno.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp is a city that boasts a diverse and vibrant nightlife, with many cafés and nightclubs situated throughout its various neighbourhoods.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The old centre and Grote Markt offer a cosy atmosphere surrounded by authentic city buildings and plenty of cafes.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The Belgians are well-known for their beer, and visitors can savor a wide range of local brews while enjoying the nightlife.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Other popular areas include het Mechelseplein, home to various cafés as well as the bustling Dageraadplaats in the belle-époque neighbourhood of Zurenborg.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The neighbourhood of het Zuid is also a popular nightlife destination, with many bars, restaurants, and cafés.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] This district is named after its nearby museums, including the Royal Museum of Fine Arts, the Museum of Contemporary Art Antwerp (M HKA), and the Photo Museum.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Het groen kwartier (the green quarter) is also a hub of cultural and artistic activity.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Het Eilandje is a neighbourhood in Antwerp, with many cafés and restaurants situated around the MAS Museum.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp is known for a diverse range of nightclubs that cater to different tastes.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Among these clubs are some of the most famous and notorious in Belgium.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Cinderella's Ballroom was famous in the 1980s.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp is a rising fashion city, and has produced designers such as the Antwerp Six.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The city has a cult status in the fashion world, due to the Royal Academy of Fine Arts, one of the most important fashion academies in the world.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] It has served as the learning centre for many Belgian fashion designers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Since the 1980s, several graduates of the Belgian Royal Academy of Fine Arts have become internationally successful fashion designers in Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The city has had a huge influence on other Belgian fashion designers such as Raf Simons, Veronique Branquinho, Olivier Theyskens and Kris Van Assche.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] In 2019, Arte won the Fashion brand of the Year award at the Belgian Fashion Awards.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The Antwerp label was founded by Bertony Da Silva in 2009.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp is famous for its local products.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] In August every year the Bollekesfeest takes place.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The Bollekesfeest is a showcase for such local products as Bolleke, an amber beer from the De Koninck Brewery.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The city's historical ale, Seefbier, dating back to the 16th century and brewed at the Antwerpse Brouw Compagnie is a testament to the city's long brewing history and one of Belgium's oldest existing beerstyles.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The Mokatine sweets made by Confiserie Roodthooft, Elixir D'Anvers, a locally made liquor, locally roasted coffee from Koffie Verheyen, sugar from Candico, Poolster pickled herring and Equinox horse meat, are other examples of local specialities.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] One of the most known products of the city are its biscuits, the *Antwerpse Handjes*, literally "Antwerp Hands".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Usually made from a short pastry with almonds or milk chocolate, they symbolize the Antwerp trademark and folklore.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The local products are represented by a non-profit organization, Streekproducten Provincie Antwerpen vzw.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp has grown into the culinary capital of Flanders and Belgium.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] It has no fewer than eleven restaurants with at least one MICHELIN star.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Zilte by Viki Geunes located in the MAS museum even received the ultimate award of three stars.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The city of Antwerp was co-host for the 2021 World Choir Games together with the city of Ghent.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Organised by the Interkultur Foundation, the World Choir Games is the biggest choral competition and festival in the world.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] A number of Christian missions to seafarers are based in Antwerp.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] These include the Mission to Seafarers, British & International Sailors' Society, the Finnish Seamen's Mission, the Norwegian Sjømannskirken and the Apostleship of the Sea.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] They provide cultural and social activities as well as religious services.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The iconic Italiëlei premises have been closed down and all activities have been moved to the Antwerp Harbour Hotel on Noorderlaan.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp held the 1920 Summer Olympics, which were the first games after the First World War and also the only ones to be held in Belgium.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp hosted the World Artistic Gymnastics Championships in 2013 and 2023 in the Sportpaleis.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Annually Antwerp hosts the European Open ATP Tour 250 tennis tournament that takes place in Antwerp's Sport Palace.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] It was introduced for the 2016 ATP World Tour.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Another annual event is the Antwerp 10 miles and the Antwerp marathon.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] For the year 2013, Antwerp was awarded the title of European Capital of Sport.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp is home of two professional football clubs being, Royal Antwerp F.C., currently playing in the Belgian First Division, founded in 1880 and is known as 'The Great Old' for being the first club registered to the Royal Belgian Football Association in 1895.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Over the course of the club's history, Royal Antwerp have won five Belgian league titles as well as four Belgian Cups.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp F.C. is also a member of the Club of Pioneers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Another club in the city is K Beerschot VA, founded in 1899 by former Royal Antwerp players.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] They play at the Olympisch Stadion, the main venue of the 1920 Olympics.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Between these two football teams there has always been a big rivalry.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] When the two play against each other the stadiums are packed and the passioned fans give a great display of their passion, but this has also led to fights, hooliganism and vandalism.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The Antwerp Giants play in the BNXT league, the league is the first tier in both the Dutch and Belgian system.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp has won the Belgian championship once, in 2000.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The city's Groenplaats hosted the official 2022 FIBA 3x3 World Cup.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] Antwerp has a university and several colleges.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The University of Antwerp (*Universiteit Antwerpen*) was established in 2003, following the merger of the RUCA, UFSIA and UIA institutes.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The university has approximately 23,000 registered students, making it the third-largest university in Flanders, as well as 1,800 foreign students.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] It has 7 faculties, spread over four campus locations in the city centre and in the south of the city.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The university is part of Young Universities for the Future of Europe (YUFE) and Young European Research Universities Network (YERUN).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The KU Leuven has a presence in Antwerp too.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] The city has several colleges, including Antwerp Management School (AMS), the Antwerp Maritime Academy, the Karel de Grote University of Applied Sciences and Arts and AP Hogeschool Antwerpen.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/antwerp-p02] AP Hogeschool has about 15,000 students and 1,600 staff, and the Karel de Grote Hogeschool has about 13,500 students and 1,300 staff.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] On 23 September 1338, at the start of the Hundred Years' War between England and France, a naval battle was held near Arnemuiden.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] It was the first naval battle of the Hundred Years' War and the first naval battle using artillery, as the English ship *Christofer* had three cannons and one handgun.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] In 1573, Arnemuiden was destroyed by Spanish troops and more than 300 citizens were killed.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] Even though only a couple of hundred people were left, it received city rights in 1574.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] Until 1997, Arnemuiden was a separate municipality.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] Arnemuiden has a railway station - Arnemuiden railway station.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] A substantial part of the inhabitants of Arnemuiden have been a fisherman in some part of their life.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] This explains the immense popularity of tattoos and fishing ship earrings in the village.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/arnemuiden] "De klok van Arnemuiden" is a Dutch song about the church clock at the Arnemuiden central market.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] The **battle of Ardres** was a battle that took place on 8 June 1351 by forces from the Kingdom of France, led by Édouard I de Beaujeu, near the English-held town of Ardres, in a ditch in a river bend, as a part of the Hundred Years' War.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] In the battle Beajeau was killed and the English commander, John de Beauchamp was captured.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] Since the Norman Conquest of England in 1066, English monarchs had held titles and lands within France, the possession of which made them vassals of the kings of France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] The status of the English kings' French fiefs was a major source of conflict between the two monarchies throughout the Middle Ages.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] Following a series of disagreements between Philip VI of France (r.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] 1327–1377), on 24 May 1337 Philip's Great Council in Paris agreed that the Duchy of Aquitaine, modern-day Gascony, should be taken back into Philip's hands on the ground that Edward was in breach of his obligations as a vassal.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] This marked the start of the Hundred Years' War, which was to last 116 years.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] In early June 1351, a large French force led by Édouard I de Beaujeu and Geoffroi de Charny, came upon a sizeable English raiding party under the command of John de Beauchamp, Calais' military governor.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] The English forces amounted to 300 men-at-arms and 300 mounted archers from the Saint-Omer garrison.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] As the battle started, the French surrounded the English and began to repeatedly attack.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] After two unsuccessful French ambushes, de Beauchamp sent his forces back to Calais with the wounded and plunder.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] They were followed by the French, and on 8 June he decided to fight the 1,500 men-at-arms pursuing them.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] He set up his forces in a river bend behind a wide ditch to have a defensive position.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] The river where the battle took place was near the English-held town of Ardres.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] Beaujeu was killed at the start of the battle.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] However, the larger French force advanced on foot towards the English anyways.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] The English archers ran out of arrows and decided to charge the French.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] However, this did not have any substantial effect, as soon after the heavily wounded English forces were defeated by a French cavalry reinforcement from Saint-Omer.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] Beauchamp was captured along with many of his men, and the French won the battle.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] After a large amount of the Calais garrison's men were killed or captured in the battle, it was left very very weakened and susceptible to French capture.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-ardres] However the French were not able to capitalize on this before reinforcements from the garrison arrived.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-arnemuiden] The **Battle of Arnemuiden** was a naval battle fought on 23 September 1338 at the start of the Hundred Years' War between England and France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-arnemuiden] It was the first naval battle of the Hundred Years' War and the first recorded European naval battle using artillery, as the English ship *Christopher* had three cannons and one handgun.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-arnemuiden] The battle featured a vast French fleet under admirals Hugues Quiéret and Nicolas Béhuchet against a small squadron of five great English cogs transporting an enormous cargo of wool to Antwerp, where Edward III of England was hoping to sell it, in order to be able to pay subsidies to his allies.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-arnemuiden] It occurred near Arnemuiden, the port of the island of Walcheren (now in the Netherlands, but then part of the County of Flanders, formally part of the Kingdom of France).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-arnemuiden] Overwhelmed by the superior numbers and with some of their crew still on shore, John Kingston, the commander of the squadron, surrendered after a day's fighting.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-arnemuiden] The French captured the rich cargo, took the five cogs into their fleet and massacred the English prisoners.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-arnemuiden] — Collection des chroniques nationales françaises écrites en langue vulgaire du treizième au seizième siècle, avec notes et éclaircissements par J.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The **Battle of Auberoche** was fought on 21 October 1345 during the Gascon campaign of 1345 between an Anglo-Gascon force of 1,200 men under Henry, Earl of Derby, and a French army of 7,000 commanded by Louis of Poitiers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] It was fought at the village of Auberoche near Périgueux in northern Aquitaine.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] At the time, Gascony was a territory of the English Crown and the "English" army included a large proportion of native Gascons.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The battle resulted in a heavy defeat for the French, who suffered very high casualties, with their leaders killed or captured.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The battle took place during the early stages of the Hundred Years' War.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Along with the Battle of Bergerac earlier in the year, it marked a change in the military balance of power in the region as the French position subsequently collapsed.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] It was one of a series of victories which would lead to Henry of Lancaster being called "one of the best warriors in the world" by a contemporary chronicler.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Over the centuries, English holdings in France had varied in size, but by 1337 only Gascony in south-western France and Ponthieu in northern France were left.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The independent-minded Gascons had their own customs and claimed to have a separate language.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] A large proportion of the enormous quantity of red wine that they produced was shipped to England in a profitable trade.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The Gascons preferred their relationship with a distant English king who left them alone to one with a French king who would interfere in their affairs.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Before the war commenced at least 1,000 ships a year departed Gascony.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Among their cargoes were over 80,000 tuns of wine.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The duty levied by the English Crown on wine from Bordeaux, the capital of Gascony, was more than all other English customs duties combined and by far the largest source of state income.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Bordeaux had a population of over 50,000, greater than London's, and Bordeaux was possibly richer.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] However, by this time English Gascony had become so truncated by French encroachments that it relied on imports of food, largely from England.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Any interruptions to regular shipping were liable to starve Gascony and financially cripple England; the French were well aware of this.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] French monarchs systematically sought to check the growth of English power, stripping away lands as the opportunity arose.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Towards the end of 1336, following a series of disagreements between Philip VI of France (r.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] 1327–1377), Philip decided that war was the only way to drive the English out for good.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] On 24 May 1337, Philip's Great Council in Paris agreed that the Duchy of Aquitaine, effectively Gascony, should be taken back into Philip's hands on the grounds that Edward was in breach of his obligations as a vassal.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Although Gascony was the cause of the war, Edward was able to spare few resources for its defence, and previously when an English army had campaigned on the continent it had operated in northern France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] In most campaigning seasons the Gascons had to rely on their own resources and had been hard pressed by the French.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] In 1339 the French besieged Bordeaux, the capital of Gascony, even breaking into the city with a large force before they were repulsed.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Typically the Gascons could field 3,000–6,000 men, the large majority infantry, although up to two-thirds of them would be tied down in garrisons.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] There was no formal border between English and French territory.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Many landholders owned a patchwork of widely separated estates, perhaps owing fealty to a different overlord for each, or holding some rights from the French Crown as the monarch and others from the English Crown as their liege lord.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Each small estate was likely to have a fortified tower or keep, with larger estates having castles.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Fortifications were also constructed at transport choke points, to collect tolls and to restrict military passage; fortified towns grew up alongside all bridges and most fords over the many rivers in the region.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Military forces could support themselves by foraging so long as they moved on at frequent intervals.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] If they wished to remain in one place for any length of time, as was necessary to besiege a castle, then access to water transport was essential for supplies of food and fodder, and desirable for such items as siege equipment.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Warfare was usually a struggle for possession of castles and other fortified points, and for the mutable loyalty of the local nobility; the region had been in a state of flux for centuries and many local lords served whichever monarch was considered the stronger, regardless of national ties.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] By 1345, after eight years of war, English-controlled territory mostly consisted of a coastal strip from Bordeaux to Bayonne, with isolated strongholds further inland.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The French had strong fortifications throughout what had once been English-controlled Gascony.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Edward determined early in 1345 to attack France on three fronts.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The Earl of Northampton would lead a small force to Brittany, a slightly larger force would proceed to Gascony under the command of Henry, Earl of Derby, and the main force would accompany Edward to northern France or Flanders.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The previous Seneschal of Gascony, Nicholas de la Beche, was replaced by the more senior Ralph, Earl of Stafford, who sailed for Gascony in February with an advance force.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby was appointed the King's Lieutenant in Gascony on 13 March 1345 and received a contract to raise a force of 2,000 men in England, and further troops in Gascony itself.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The highly detailed contract of indenture had a term of six months from the opening of the campaign in Gascony, with an option for Edward III to extend it for a further six months on the same terms.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby was given a high degree of autonomy; for example, his strategic instructions were: *si guerre soit, et a faire le bien q'il poet* ("if there is war, do the best you can").
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] In early 1345 the French decided to stand on the defensive in the south west.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Their intelligence correctly predicted English offensives in the three theatres, but they did not have the money to raise a significant army in each.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] They anticipated, correctly, that the English planned to make their main effort in northern France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Thus they directed what resources they had there, planning to assemble their main army at Arras on 22 July.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] South-western France was encouraged to rely on its own resources, but as the Truce of Malestroit, signed in early 1343, was still in effect, the local lords were reluctant to spend money, and little was done.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby's force embarked at Southampton at the end of May.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Due to bad weather, his fleet of 151 ships was forced to shelter in Falmouth for several weeks en route, finally departing on 23 July.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The Gascons, primed by Stafford to expect Derby's arrival in late May and sensing the French weakness, took the field without him.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The Gascons captured the large, weakly garrisoned castles of Montravel and Monbreton on the Dordogne in early June; both were taken by surprise and their seizure broke the tenuous Truce of Malestroit.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Stafford made a short advance north to besiege Blaye with his advance party and perhaps 1,000 men-at-arms and 3,000 infantry of the Gascon lords.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Having established the siege he left the Gascons to prosecute it and proceeded to Langon, south of Bordeaux, and set up a second siege.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The Anglo-Gascon forces at both sieges could be readily supplied by ship.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The French issued an urgent call to arms.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Meanwhile, small independent parties of Gascons raided across the region.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Local French groups joined them, and several minor nobles threw in their lot with the Anglo-Gascons.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] They had several significant successes, but their main effect was to tie down most of the weak French garrisons in the region and to cause them to call for reinforcements.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The few mobile French troops in the region immobilised themselves with sieges: of Casseneuil in the Agenais; Monchamp near Condom; and Montcuq, a strong but strategically insignificant castle south of Bergerac.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Large areas were effectively undefended.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Edward III's main army sailed on 29 June.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] They anchored off Sluys (Sluis) in Flanders until 22 July, while Edward attended to diplomatic affairs.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] When they sailed, probably intending to land in Normandy, they were scattered by a storm and found their way to various English ports over the following week.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] After more than five weeks on board ship, the men and horses had to be disembarked.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] There was a further week's delay while the King and his council debated what to do, by which time it proved impossible to take any action with the main English army before winter.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Aware of this, Philip VI despatched reinforcements to Brittany and Gascony.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Peter, Duke of Bourbon was appointed French commander in Gascony on 8 August and based himself at Agen.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] On 9 August 1345, Derby arrived in Bordeaux with 500 men-at-arms, 500 mounted archers and 1,000 English and Welsh foot archers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] After two weeks recruiting and organising, Derby marched his force to Langon, rendezvoused with Stafford and took command of the combined force.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Stafford had to this point pursued a cautious strategy of small-scale sieges.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby's intention was quite different; rather than continue a cautious war of sieges he was determined to strike directly at the French main force before it was fully assembled.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The French, hearing of Derby's arrival, concentrated their forces at the strategically important town of Bergerac, where there was an important bridge over the Dordogne River.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] After a council of war, Derby decided to strike at the French there.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The capture of the town, which had good river supply links to Bordeaux, would provide the Anglo-Gascon army with a base from which to carry the war to the French.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] It would also force the lifting of the siege of the nearby allied castle of Montcuq and sever communications between French forces north and south of the Dordogne.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The English believed that if the French field army could be beaten or distracted the town could be easily taken.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby moved rapidly and took the French army by surprise, defeating them in a running battle.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] French casualties were heavy, with many killed and a large number captured, including their commander.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The surviving French from their field army rallied around John, Count of Armagnac, and retreated north to Périgueux.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Within days of the battle, Bergerac fell to an Anglo-Gascon assault and was subsequently sacked.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] After consolidating and reorganising for two weeks Derby left a large garrison in the town and moved north to the Anglo-Gascon stronghold of Mussidan in the Isle valley with 6,000–8,000 men.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] He then pushed west to Périgueux, the provincial capital, taking several strongpoints on the way.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The city's defences were antiquated and derelict, but the size of the French force defending it prohibited an assault.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby blockaded Périgueux and captured strongholds blocking the main routes into the city.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] John, Duke of Normandy, the son and heir of Philip VI, gathered an army reportedly numbering over 20,000 and manoeuvred in the area.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] In early October a very large detachment relieved the city and drove off Derby's force, which withdrew towards Bordeaux.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Further reinforced, the French started besieging the English-held strongpoints.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The main French force of 7,000, commanded by Louis of Poitiers, besieged the castle of Auberoche, nine miles (14 km) east of Périgueux.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Auberoche perches on a rocky promontory completely commanding the River Auvézère and the valley road at a point where the valley narrows almost to a gorge.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The small Anglo-Gascon garrison was commanded by Frank van Hallen.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The French encampment was divided in two, with the majority of the soldiers camped close to the river between the castle and village, while a smaller force was situated to prevent any relief attempts from the north.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The chronicler Froissart tells a tale, most likely apocryphal, that a soldier attempting to reach English lines with a letter requesting help was captured and returned to the castle via a trebuchet.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] A messenger did get through French lines and reached Derby, who was already returning to the area with a scratch force of 1,200 English and Gascon soldiers: 400 men-at-arms and 800 mounted archers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Knowing he was outnumbered, Derby waited near Périgueux for several days for the arrival of a force under the Earl of Pembroke.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Unknown to Derby, another French army of some 9,000 to 10,000 men under the Duke of Normandy was only 25 miles (40 km) away.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby personally reconnoitred the French position.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Still hoping for the last-minute arrival of Pembroke, Derby called a council of his officers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] It was decided that rather than wait and possibly lose the advantage of surprise, the army would attack immediately and attempt to overrun the French camp before an effective defence could be devised.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The attack was launched as the French were having their evening meal, and complete surprise was achieved.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] His longbowmen shot from the treeline to the west into the French position.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The French, packed tightly into the narrow meadow, not expecting an attack and unarmoured, are reported to have taken heavy casualties from this.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Adam Murimuth, a contemporary chronicler, estimates French casualties at this stage at around 1,000.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] While the French were confused and distracted by this attack from the west, Derby made a cavalry charge with his 400 men-at-arms from the south.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] They had some 200 to 300 yards (200 to 300 m) across flat ground to cover to reach the French.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] French soldiers struggled into their armour and their commanders rallied their still superior forces.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] A small number of Anglo-Gascon infantry had followed a path in the woods to emerge in the French rear and attacked from the north-west.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The fighting continued in the area of the camp for some time.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Hallen realised that the French troops guarding his exit from the castle were either distracted or had been drawn off to join the fighting; he sallied with all the mounted men he could muster and took the French in the rear.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] At this further unexpected attack the French defence collapsed and they routed, pursued by the English cavalry.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Those French still holding their position in the small camp to the north fled without fighting.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] French casualties are uncertain, but were heavy.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Murimuth states that French fatalities caused by the archers alone were 700 men-at-arms and over 1,000 infantry.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Total casualties are variously described by modern historians as "appalling", "extremely high", "staggering", and "heavy".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Many French nobles were taken prisoner; lesser men were, as was customary, put to the sword.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The French commander, Louis of Poitiers, died of his wounds.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Surviving prisoners included the second-in-command, Bertrand de l'Isle-Jourdain, two counts, seven viscounts, three barons, the seneschals of Clermont and Toulouse, a nephew of the Pope and so many knights that they were not counted.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The French left behind them a large quantity of loot and supplies.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] This was in addition to the ransoms extracted from the French captives for their release, which was due to the individuals who had captured them, shared with their liege lords.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The ransoms alone made a fortune for many of the soldiers in Derby's army, as well as Derby himself, who was said to have made at least £50,000 (£60,000,000 as of 2025) from the day's captives, approximately equal to Edward III's annual income.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Over the following year Philip VI paid large amounts from the royal treasury as contributions towards the captives' ransoms.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The Duke of Normandy lost heart on hearing of the defeat.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Despite outnumbering the Anglo-Gascon force eight to one he retreated to Angoulême and disbanded his army.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The French also abandoned all of their ongoing sieges of other Anglo-Gascon garrisons.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby was left almost completely unopposed for six months, during which he seized more towns, including Montségur, La Réole and Aiguillon and greatly increased English territory and influence in south-west France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Local morale, and more importantly prestige in the border region, had decidedly swung England's way following this conflict, providing an influx of taxes and recruits for the English armies.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Local lords of note declared for the English, bringing significant retinues with them.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The four-month campaign has been described as "the first successful land campaign of... the Hundred Years' War", which had commenced more than eight years earlier.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] With this success, the English had established a regional dominance which would last over thirty years.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Modern historians have praised the generalship demonstrated by Derby in this campaign: "superb and innovative tactician"; "ris[ing] to the level of genius"; "brilliant in the extreme"; "stunning"; "brilliant".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] The *Chronique des quatre premiers Valois*, written fifty years after the event, describes him as "one of the best warriors in the world".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] Derby went on to lead another successful campaign in 1346.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-auberoche] UK Consumer Price Index inflation figures from 1209–2024 based on data from *"Inflation calculator".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The **Battle of Bergerac** was fought between Anglo-Gascon and French forces at the town of Bergerac, Gascony, in August 1345 during the Hundred Years' War.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] In early 1345 Edward III of England decided to launch a major attack on the French from the north, while sending smaller forces to Brittany and Gascony, the latter being both economically important to the English war effort and the proximate cause of the war.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The French focused on the threat to northern France, leaving comparatively small forces in the south-west.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Henry of Grosmont, Earl of Derby, arrived in Gascony in August and, breaking with the previous policy of cautious advance, struck directly at the largest French concentration, at Bergerac.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] He surprised and defeated the French forces under Bertrand I of L'Isle-Jourdain and Henri de Montigny.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The French suffered heavy casualties and the loss of the town, a significant strategic setback.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Along with the Battle of Auberoche later in the year, it marked a change in the military balance of power in the region.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] It was the first of a series of victories which would lead to Henry of Derby being called "one of the best warriors in the world" by a contemporary chronicler.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Since the Norman Conquest of 1066, English monarchs had held titles and lands within France, the possession of which made them vassals of the kings of France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The French began re-taking these lands from the English in the late 12th century; by 1337 only Gascony in south-western France and Ponthieu in northern France were left.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The duty levied by the English Crown on wine from Bordeaux, the capital of Gascony, was more than all other customs duties combined and by far the largest source of state income.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Although Gascony was the cause of the war, Edward was able to spare few resources for it, and previously when an English army had campaigned on the continent it had operated in northern France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] In most campaigning seasons the Gascons had had to rely on their own resources and had been hard pressed by the French.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The border between English and French territory in Gascony was extremely unclear.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Many landholders owned a patchwork of widely separated estates, perhaps owing fealty to a different overlord for each.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] If they wished to remain in one place for any length of time, as was necessary to besiege a castle, then access to water transport was essential for supplies of food and fodder and desirable for such items as siege equipment.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Warfare was usually a struggle for possession of castles and other fortified points, and for the mutable loyalty of the local nobility; the region had been in a state of flux for centuries and many local lords served whichever country was stronger, regardless of national ties.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The Earl of Northampton would lead a small force to Brittany, a slightly larger force would proceed to Gascony under the command of Henry, Earl of Derby and the main force would accompany Edward to France or Flanders.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The highly detailed contract of indenture had a term of six months from the opening of the campaign in Gascony, with an option for Edward III to extend it for a further six-month on the same terms.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Derby was given a high degree of autonomy, for example his strategic instructions were: "si guerre soit, et a faire le bien q'il poet" (if there is war, do the best you can).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] In early 1345 the French decided to stand on the defensive in the south-west.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Thus, they directed what resources they had to there, planning to assemble their main army at Arras on 22 July.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Having established the siege, he left the Gascons to prosecute it and proceeded to Langon, south of Bordeaux, and set up a second siege.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] A number of local French groups joined them, and several minor nobles threw in their lot with the Anglo-Gascons.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] They anchored off Sluys in Flanders until 22 July, while Edward attended to diplomatic affairs.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] After more than five weeks on board ship the men and horses had to be disembarked.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] On 9 August 1345 Derby arrived in Bordeaux with 500 men-at-arms, 500 mounted archers and 1,000 English and Welsh foot archers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] After two weeks recruiting and organising Derby marched his force to Langon, rendezvoused with Stafford and took command of the combined force.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Derby's intention was quite different, rather than continue a cautious war of sieges he was determined to strike directly at the French main force before it was fully assembled.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The French, hearing of Derby's arrival, concentrated their forces at the strategically important town of Bergerac, where there was an important bridge over the Dordogne, under the command of Bertrand de l'Isle-Jourdain.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] They would also be within reach of the French force under Henri de Montigny, Seneschal of Périgord, besieging nearby Montcuq.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] After a council of war Derby decided to attack the French here.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Sometime in mid-August Derby marched from Langon with 1,200 men-at-arms, of whom 700 were Gascons, 1,500 longbowmen and 2,800 Gascon infantry.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The French around Bergerac and Montcuq had 1,600 men-at-arms and a large but unspecified number of other troops.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Derby's army moved fast and took the French forces by surprise.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The exact date of the battle is unknown; A.H.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Burne gives the fall of Bergerac as 26 August but holds that the battle took place some days before, while Kenneth Fowler gives the date of the fall of Bergerac as 24 August.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Exactly where the first part of the battle took place is also unknown.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The modern historian Clifford Rogers makes the case for the road between St.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Fowler believes it was on the road from Montcuq to Bergerac.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The French, either lured from Bergerac by a ruse or in the process of withdrawing from their siege of Montcuq, or both, were caught on the road by the Anglo-Gascon army.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] They were subject to a barrage of English archery and struck by a charge by the Anglo-Gascon men-at-arms.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The French were routed, and a running fight took place as they fled toward the St.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Madeleine suburb of Bergerac, at the south end of the bridge.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Because the pursuit was so close, it was impossible to close the gates on the barbican at the south end of the bridge and it was overrun.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The pursuers pressed on to the bridge, which was 200 yards (180 m) long, narrow, and obstructed halfway along by a chapel.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The garrison attempted to sortie to secure the barbican and the bridge became jammed with Frenchmen.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] English archers waded out to sandbanks in the river and enfiladed the panic-stricken French from both flanks.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] They "were killed in great numbers" and many surrendered to the Anglo-Gascons pressing close behind them.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Attempts to drop the portcullis on the north end of the bridge were thwarted by a wounded horse falling in the gateway.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The Anglo-Gascons pressed on to attack the town itself.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] At this point, the contemporary sources differ.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The two main chronicles covering the whole war, Froissart's *The Chronicles of England, France and Spain* and the *St.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Omer Chronicle*, state that the gate was closed and that the town withstood a siege for several days, falling only after Derby had boats brought up-river to enable an attack on the weak riverside wall.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] A larger group of 14th-century sources, including the two which focus specifically on the war in Gascony, the *Chronique de Guyenne* and the *Chronique de Brazas*, state that the gate was carried by the first assault, on the same day as the battle, and after nightfall.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] There is other documentary evidence to support this opinion and it is generally accepted by modern historians, such as Rogers and Jonathan Sumption.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] In any event, whether several days later or on the evening of the battle, the town was captured and sacked, and a large amount of supplies and horses was captured.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The surviving French from the field army which had been besieging Montcuq were gathered by John, Count of Armagnac, and retreated north to Périgueux.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] The battle and subsequent capture of Bergerac were major victories; the plunder from the defeated French army and from sacking the town was immense.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Over 600 French men-at-arms were listed as killed, and a large number were captured.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Losses among the French infantry are not recorded but were reported to have been heavy; as was customary, most of the common soldiers were killed, regardless of whether they were still bearing arms.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Prisoners included Henri de Montingny, ten other noblemen and a large number of lesser nobles.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Derby's share of the ransoms and the loot was estimated at £34,000 (£41,000,000 in 2025 terms), approximately four times the annual income from his lands.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] English and Gascon losses were very light.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Modern historian Nicholas Gribit has described Derby's four-month campaign of 1345 as "the first successful land campaign of ... the Hundred Years' War".
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Strategically, the Anglo-Gascon army had secured an important base for further operations.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-bergerac] Politically, local lords who had been undecided in their allegiance had been shown that the English were again a force to be reckoned with in Gascony.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The **Battle of Blanchetaque** was fought on 24 August 1346 between an English army under King Edward III and a French force commanded by Godemar du Fay.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The battle was part of the Crécy campaign, which took place during the early stages of the Hundred Years' War.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] After landing in the Cotentin Peninsula on 12 July, the English army had burnt a path of destruction through some of the richest lands in France to within 20 miles (32 km) of Paris, sacking a number of towns on the way.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The English then marched north, hoping to link up with an allied Flemish army which had invaded from Flanders.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] They were outmanoeuvred by the French king, Philip VI, who garrisoned all of the bridges and fords over the River Somme and followed the English with his own field army.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The area had previously been stripped of food stocks by the French, and the English were essentially trapped.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Hearing of a ford at Blanchetaque, 10 miles (16 km) from the sea, Edward marched for it and encountered the blocking force under du Fay.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Once the ebbing tide had lowered the water level, a force of English longbowmen marched partway across the ford and, standing in the water, engaged a force of mercenary crossbowmen, whose shooting they were able to suppress.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] A French cavalry force attempted to push back the longbowmen but were in turn attacked by English men-at-arms.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] After a mêlée in the river, the French were pushed back, more English troops were fed into the fight, and the French broke and fled.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] French casualties were reported as over half of their force, while English losses were light.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Two days after Blanchetaque, the main French army under Philip was defeated at the Battle of Crécy with heavy loss of life.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Edward ended the campaign by laying siege to Calais, which fell after twelve months, securing an English entrepôt into northern France which was held for two hundred years.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The status of the English king's French fiefs was a major source of conflict between the two kingdoms throughout the Middle Ages.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] English holdings in France had varied in size over the centuries, but by 1337 only Gascony in south-western France and Ponthieu in northern France were left.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] 1327–1377), Philip's Great Council in Paris on 24 May 1337 agreed that the Duchy of Aquitaine, effectively Gascony, should be taken back into Philip's hands on the grounds that Edward was in breach of his obligations as a vassal.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] This marked the start of the Hundred Years' War.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Early in 1345, Edward determined to attack France on three fronts: a small force would sail for Brittany; a slightly larger force would proceed to Gascony under the command of the Henry, Earl of Derby; and the main force would accompany him to either northern France or Flanders.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The French anticipated, correctly, that the English planned to make their main effort in northern France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Thus, they directed what resources they had to the north, planning to assemble their main army at Arras on 22 July.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] South-western France and Brittany were encouraged to rely on their own resources.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The main English army sailed on 29 June 1345 and anchored off Sluys in Flanders.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Edward was unexpectedly threatened with the loss of his Flemish allies, and to avoid this was forced to attend to diplomatic affairs.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] By 22 July, although the Flemish situation was unresolved, men and horses could be confined on board ship no longer and the fleet sailed, probably intending to land in Normandy.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] It was scattered by a storm, and individual ships found their way over the following week to various English ports where they disembarked.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] There was a further week's delay while the King and his council debated what to do, by which time it proved impossible to do anything major with the main English army before winter.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] During 1345, Derby led a whirlwind campaign through Gascony at the head of an Anglo-Gascon army.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] He heavily defeated two large French armies at the battles of Bergerac and Auberoche, captured French towns and fortifications in much of Périgord and most of Agenais, and gave the English possessions in Gascony strategic depth.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] John, Duke of Normandy, the son and heir of Philip VI, was placed in charge of all French forces in south-west France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] In March 1346 a French army numbering between 15,000 and 20,000, enormously superior to any force the Anglo-Gascons could field, including all the military officers of the royal household, marched on Gascony.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] They besieged the strategically and logistically important town of Aiguillon, "the key to the Gascon plain", on 1 April.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] On 2 April the *arrière-ban*, the formal call to arms for all able-bodied males, was announced for the south of France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] French financial, logistical and manpower efforts were focused on this offensive.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Meanwhile, Edward was raising a fresh army, and assembled more than 700 vessels to transport it – the largest English fleet ever to that date.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The French were aware of Edward's efforts, but given the extreme difficulty of disembarking an army other than at a port, and the existence of friendly ports in Brittany and Gascony, the French assumed that Edward would sail for one of the latter – probably Gascony – to relieve Aiguillon.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] To guard against any possibility of an English landing in northern France, Philip relied on his powerful navy.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] This reliance was misplaced given the difficulty naval forces of the time had in effectively interdicting opposing fleets, and the French were unable to prevent Edward successfully crossing the Channel.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The campaign began on 11 July 1346, when Edward's fleet departed the south of England.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The fleet landed the next day at Saint-Vaast-la-Hougue, 20 miles (32 km) from Cherbourg.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The English army is estimated by modern historians to have been some 15,000 strong and consisted of both English and Welsh soldiers combined with a number of German and Breton mercenaries and allies.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] It included at least one Norman baron who was unhappy with the rule of Philip VI.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The English achieved complete strategic surprise and marched south.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Edward's aim was to conduct a chevauchée, a large-scale raid, across French territory to reduce his opponent's morale and wealth.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] His soldiers razed every town in their path and looted whatever they could from the populace.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The towns of Carentan, Saint-Lô and Torteval were destroyed as the army passed, along with many other smaller places.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The English fleet paralleled the army's route, devastating the country for up to 5 miles (8 km) inland and taking vast amounts of loot; many ships deserted, having filled their holds.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] They also captured or burnt over 100 French ships, 61 of which had been converted into military vessels.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Caen, the cultural, political, religious and financial centre of north-west Normandy, was stormed on 26 July and subsequently looted for five days.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The English marched out towards the River Seine on 1 August.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The French military position was difficult.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Their main army was committed to the intractable siege of Aiguillon in the south-west.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] After his surprise landing in Normandy, Edward was devastating some of the richest lands in France and flaunting his ability to march at will through France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] On 2 August, a small English force supported by a large number of Flemings invaded France from Flanders.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] French defences were completely inadequate.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] On 29 July, Philip proclaimed the *arrière-ban* for northern France, ordering every able-bodied male to assemble at Rouen, where Philip himself arrived on the 31st.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] He immediately moved west against Edward with an ill-organised and poorly-equipped army.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Five days later he returned to Rouen and broke the bridge over the Seine behind him.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] On 7 August, the English reached the Seine, 12 miles (19 km) south of Rouen, and raided up to its suburbs.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Philip, under pressure from representatives of the Pope, sent envoys offering peace backed by a marriage alliance; Edward replied that he was not prepared to lose marching time to futile discussion and dismissed them.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] By 12 August, Edward's army was encamped at Poissy, 20 miles from Paris, having left a 40-mile-wide (60 km) swath of destruction down the left bank of the Seine to within 2 miles (3 km) of the city.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] On 16 August, Edward burnt down Poissy and marched north.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The French had carried out a scorched earth policy, carrying away all stores of food and so forcing the English to spread out over a wide area to forage, which greatly slowed them.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Bands of French peasants attacked some of the smaller groups of foragers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Philip reached the River Somme a day's march ahead of Edward.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] He based himself at Amiens and sent large detachments to hold every bridge and ford across the Seine between Amiens and the sea.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The English were now trapped in an area which had been stripped of food.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The French moved out of Amiens and advanced westwards, towards the English.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] They were now willing to give battle, knowing that they would have the advantage of being able to stand on the defensive while the English were forced to try and fight their way past them.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Edward was determined to break the French blockade of the Somme and probed at several points, vainly attacking Hangest and Pont-Remy before moving west along the river.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] English supplies were running out and the army was ragged, starving and beginning to suffer from a drop in morale.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] On the evening of 24 August, the English were encamped north of Acheux while the French were 6 miles (10 km) away at Abbeville.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] During the night Edward was made aware, either by an Englishman living locally or by a French captive, that just 4 miles (6 km) away, near the village of Saigneville, was a ford named Blanchetaque (so named for the white stones lining the river's bed).
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Edward immediately broke camp and moved his whole force toward the ford.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] When the English arrived at the river they discovered that the French had defended the ford strongly.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Guarding the far side of the crossing were 3,500 soldiers, including 500 men-at-arms and an unknown number of mercenary crossbowmen under Godemar du Fay, an experienced French general.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] A contemporary chronicler described this as an elite unit.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The ford was 2,000 yards (1,800 m) wide and as it was only 10 miles (16 km) from the coast, it was strongly tidal, only passable for a few hours twice each day.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] When the English arrived at dawn, the tide was high and not expected to drop to crossable levels for several hours.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The French force was drawn up in three lines along the sloping north bank, with the best soldiers, the 500 men-at-arms, positioned in the centre.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] At about 9 a.m., a force of English longbowmen, led by Hugh, Baron Despenser, started across the ford, 12 abreast on the narrow causeway.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] They came under crossbow shot, but continued until the water was shallow enough for them to be able to reply.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The numbers shooting from each side at this stage are not known, but the longbowmen had the advantages that those to the rear were able to send arrows over the heads of those in front of them, and that they could shoot three times faster than the crossbowmen.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The English archery proved more effective than the French crossbow shot.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] As their crossbowmen were overcome, some French men-at-arms mounted and entered the river in an attempt to ride down the longbowmen.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The opposing cavalry, having moved into contact at walking pace, suffered few casualties.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The greater pressure of the English forced the mêlée onto the French bank of the river.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The dismounted French men-at-arms were pushed back by the mass of retreating French and advancing English men-at-arms, making space for the English longbowmen to gain the riverbank.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The longbowmen were themselves being forced forward by more English cavalry advancing behind them.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] More and more English were fed into the bridgehead and after a short, sharp struggle, the French broke, fleeing for Abbeville, 6 miles (10 km) away.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] It seems that most of the knightly and noble French participants, being mounted, successfully escaped.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The French infantry were unable to outrun the pursuing English cavalry and suffered heavy casualties.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] As was usual, no quarter was offered to the common soldiers.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Du Fay was seriously wounded, but escaped.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] An hour and a half after the French lines had broken, the entire English army was across the ford.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The main French army was close enough behind them to capture a number of English stragglers and the slower of their wagons.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] However, the tide was turning, and the French halted, facing the English across the river for the rest of the 24th, debating whether to attempt to force the crossing at the evening low tide.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] They decided not to and on the morning of the 25th backtracked to the bridge at Abbeville, a 12-mile diversion.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Casualties in the action are not clear, but it is claimed by a contemporary chronicler that as many as 2,000 French soldiers were killed in the battle or the rout which followed it.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] English losses are not known but were probably light.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] Once the French withdrew, Edward marched the 9 miles (14 km) to Crécy-en-Ponthieu where he prepared a defensive position.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] The French had been so confident that the English could not breach the Somme line that they had not denuded the area, and the countryside was rich in food and loot.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] So the English were able to resupply, Noyelles-sur-Mer and Le Crotoy in particular yielding large stores of food, which were looted and the towns then burnt.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-blanchetaque] On 26 August the main French army under Philip was crushingly defeated here at the Battle of Crécy with heavy loss of life.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] The **Battle of Cadzand** was an early skirmish of the Hundred Years' War fought in 1337.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] It consisted of a raid on the Flemish island of Cadzand, designed to provoke a reaction and battle from the local garrison and so improve morale in England and amongst King Edward III's continental allies by providing his army with an easy victory.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] On 9 November Sir Walter Manny, with the advance troops for Edward III's continental invasion, made an attempt to take the city of Sluys, but was driven off.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] For Edward, the war had not progressed as well as had been hoped at the start of the year as vacillation by allies in the Low Countries and Germany had prevented an invasion of France from progressing as intended and setbacks in the Gascon theatre had prevented any advance there either.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] Edward's fleet was unprepared for the crossing with the main body of his army and his finances were in a parlous state owing to his having been forced to pay large stipends to European forces.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] Thus he required some symbol of his intentions against the French and a demonstration of what his forces could achieve.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] To this end he ordered Sir Walter Manny, leader of his vanguard which was already stationed in Hainaut to take a small fleet and raid the island of Cadzand, now part of the mainland Netherlands and then part of Flanders, a semi-autonomous region of France.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] Cadzand was a poor, marshy island populated by fishing villages with little in the way of plunder or importance except that it was close to the wealthy Flemish port of Sluys and thus could be used as bait for the garrison of that town.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] The garrison of Sluys, led by Sir Guy de Rickenbourg, the illegitimate son of Louis, Count of Nevers, could not let such acts occur so close to them without responding and so crossed the channel between Sluys and the island a few days later and attempted to confront Manny.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] The English commander was prepared for this and had his men formed up on the island in an ideal defensive position which allowed him to attack and destroy the Flemish force in a short, sharp action probably enabled by use of the longbow although no accounts of the fighting survive.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] Only a handful of the Flemish force were able to retreat across the channel, Guy of Flanders being captured with the other noblemen whilst the rank and file were all put to the sword.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] The battle had few longer-lasting effects, as Manny abandoned the island to its surviving inhabitants shortly after the victory.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] The allies were suitably impressed by the show of strength and the border regions of Flanders were intimidated.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] King Philip VI was also greatly affected by this development, assuming that traitors amongst the Flemings had caused the defeat and responding by a wave of terror and executions which continued for the remainder of his reign and served to alienate many of his allies and supporters.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] Ten years after the battle, when England and Flanders had become allies following an uprising in the latter, Edward III was forced to apologize and make symbolic reparations for ordering this action.
[src:battle-of-arnemuiden/battle-of-cadzand] Sluys was later the scene of a highly significant naval battle in 1340.
